If the interaction term formula_3 is small (less than the fine structure), it can be treated as a perturbation; this is the Zeeman effect proper. In the Paschen–Back effect, described below, formula_3 exceeds the LS coupling significantly (but is still small compared to formula_2). In ultra-strong magnetic fields, the magnetic-field interaction may exceed formula_2, in which case the atom can no longer exist in its normal meaning, and one talks about Landau levels instead. There are intermediate cases that are more complex than these limit cases.

